      <review reviewedMajorRelease="3" reviewedMinorRelease="0" reviewedMajorRevision="0" reviewedMinorRevision="9" reviewerId="9011fbce-fc4b-4755-890b-96728c23c4d3" reviewerName="Bo Weidema" reviewerEmail="bow@lca-net.com" reviewDate="2012-05-15">
        <details>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Dichloropropene is used as a soil fumigant. The reason for placing the dichloropropene on the generic market for pesticides is that it is a by-product of allyl chloride production (0.113 kg per kg of allyl chloride). Considering that allyl chloride production is 800 Mkg per year (Ullmanns), a production of 90.4 E6 kg dichloropropene results, which will be cleared on the generic market for pesticides (a more specific substitution may be modelled if data become available. Dichloropropene is itself - together with chloropicrin and dazomet - used as a substitute for methyl bromine which is being phased out).</text>
        </details>
        <otherDetails xml:lang="en"/>
      </review>
